# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: icd-coding
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] In health care, **diagnosis codes** are used as a tool to group and identify diseases, disorders, symptoms, poisonings, adverse effects of drugs and chemicals, injuries and other reasons for patient encounters.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] Diagnostic coding is the translation of written descriptions of diseases, illnesses and injuries into codes from a particular classification.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] In medical classification, diagnosis codes are used as part of the clinical coding process alongside intervention codes.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] Both diagnosis and intervention codes are assigned by a health professional trained in medical classification such as a clinical coder or Health Information Manager.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] Several diagnosis classification systems have been implemented to various degrees of success across the world.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] The various classifications have a focus towards a particular patient encounter type such as emergency, inpatient, outpatient, mental health as well as surgical care.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] The International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health Problems (ICD) is one of the most widely used classification systems for diagnosis coding as it allows comparability and use of mortality and morbidity data.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] As the knowledge of health and medical advances arise, the diagnostic codes are generally revised and updated to match the most up to date current body of knowledge in the field of health.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] The codes may be quite frequently revised as new knowledge is attained.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] DSM (see below) changes some of its coding to correspond to the codes in ICD.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] A number of diagnostic coding systems are implemented across the world to code the stay of patients within a typical health setting, such as a hospital.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] Diagnosis codes are generally used as a representation of admitted episodes in health care settings.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] The principal diagnosis, additional diagnoses alongside intervention codes essentially depict a patient's admission to a hospital.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] Diagnoses codes are subjected to ethical considerations as they contribute to the total coded medical record in health services areas such as a hospital.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] Hospitals that are based on Activity Based Funding and Diagnoses-Related Group Classification systems are often subjected to high end decision making that could affect the outcome of funding.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] It's important to look at the scope of diagnoses codes in terms of their application in finance.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] The diagnoses codes in particular the Principal Diagnoses and Additional Diagnoses can significantly affect the total funding that a hospital may receive for any patient admitted.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] Ethically, this highlights the fact that the assignment of the diagnoses code can be influenced by a decision to maximize reimbursement of funding.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] For example, when looking at the activity based funding model used in the public hospital system in Victoria the total coded medical record is responsible for its reflected funding.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] These decisions also affect clinical documentation by physicians as recommendations from a Health Information Service can directly affect how a clinician may document a condition that a patient may have.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] The difference between the codes assigned for confusion and delirium can alter a hospitals DRG assignment as delirium is considered a higher level code than confusion within the ICD-10 coding hierarchy in terms of severity.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] A clinical coder or Health Information Manager may feel obliged to maximize funding above the ethical requirement to be honest within their diagnostic coding; this highlights the ethical standpoint of diagnoses codes as they should be reflective of a patient's admission.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] Accuracy is a major component in diagnoses codes.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] The accurate assignment of diagnoses codes in clinical coding is essential in order to effectively depict a patient's stay within a typical health service area.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] A number of factors can contribute to the overall accuracy coding which includes medical record legibility, physician documentation, clinical coder experience, financial decision making, miscoding, as well as classification system limitations.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] The legibility of a medical record is a contributing factor in the accuracy of diagnostic coding.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] The assigned proxy that is extracting information from the medical record is dependent on the quality of the medical record.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] Factors that contribute to a medical records quality are physician documentation, handwriting legibility, compilation of forms, duplication and inaccurate patient data.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] In Australia, the legibility of records has been sufficiently maintained due to the implementation of highly detailed standards and guidelines which aim to improve the legibility of medical records.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] In particular the paper medical record standard 'AS 2828' created by Standards Australia focuses on a few key areas that are critical to maintaining a legible paper medical record.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] The following criteria should be used as a guideline when creating a medical record specific to the aid of providing clear documentation for diagnostic coding.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] Ready Identification: A coder must be able to identify the exact record being coded in order to effectively extract diagnoses codes.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] Reproducible: A coder would need to make sure that the record is reproducible in that copies can be made to aid in effective coding.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] The experience of the health professional coding a medical record is an essential variable that must be accounted for when analysing the accuracy of coding.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] Generally a coder with years of experience is able to extract all the relevant information from a medical record whether it is paper, scanned or semi-electronic.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] The diagnoses codes selected from the extraction are generally compiled and sequenced in order to represent the admission.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] An experienced coder may incorrectly assign codes due a lack of application of a classification systems relevant standards.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] An example to highlight clinical coding experience would be the standard within the Australian Coding Standards *0010 General Abstraction Guidelines*.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] These guidelines indicate that a coder must seek further detail within a record in order to correctly assign the correct diagnoses code.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] An inexperienced coder may simply just use the description from the discharge summary such as *Infarction* and may not use the correct detail which could be further found within the details of the medical record.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] This directly relates to the accuracy of diagnoses codes as the experience of the health professional coder is significant in its accuracy and contribution to finance.
[src:icd-coding/diagnosis-code] Generally, coding is a concept of modeling reality with reduced effort, but with physical copying.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] While WHO manages and publishes the base version of the ICD, several member states have modified it to better suit their needs.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] In the base classification, the code set allows for more than 14,000 different codes and permits the tracking of many new diagnoses compared to the preceding ICD-9.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Through the use of optional sub-classifications, ICD-10 allows for specificity regarding the cause, manifestation, location, severity, and type of injury or disease.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The adapted versions may differ in a number of ways; some national editions have expanded the code set even further, with some going so far as to add procedure codes.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The WHO provides detailed information about the ICD via its website – including an ICD-10 online browser and ICD training materials.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The online training includes a support forum, a self-learning tool and user guide.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The following table lists the chapter number (using Roman numerals), the code range of each chapter, and the chapter's title from the international version of the ICD-10.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Approximately 27 countries use ICD-10 for reimbursement and resource allocation in their health system, and some have made modifications to ICD to better accommodate its utility.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The unchanged international version of ICD-10 is used in 117 countries for performing cause of death reporting and statistics.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The national versions may differ from the base classification in the level of detail, incomplete adoption of a category, or the addition of procedure codes.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Introduced in 1998, ICD-10 Australian Modification (ICD-10-AM) was developed by the National Centre for Classification in Health at the University of Sydney.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] It is currently maintained by the Australian Consortium for Classification Development.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] ICD-10-AM has also been adopted by New Zealand, Ireland, Saudi Arabia and several other countries.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The provisional translation of the ICD-10 for Brazilian Portuguese was started around 1986.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Brazil was designated the Field Trial Coordinating Centre for field testing of the list's Chapter V, and the translation was then updated and modified by several contributors across the country.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] One of the final versions was proofread by J.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Leme Lopes, and the final translation was created directly from the English-language version in 1992.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Canada began using ICD-10 for mortality reporting in 2000.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] A six-year, phased implementation of ICD-10-CA for morbidity reporting began in 2001.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] It was staggered across Canada's ten provinces, with Quebec the last to make the switch.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] ICD-10-CA is available in both English- and French-language versions.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The Czech Republic adopted ICD-10 in 1994, one year after its official release by WHO.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Revisions to the international edition are adopted continuously.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The official Czech translation of ICD-10 2016 10th Revision was published in 2018.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] ICD-10 was first introduced into the psychiatric health service system on January 1, 1994.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Estonia adopted ICD-10 from January 1, 1997, via a ministerial degree.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] However, chapter V "Mental and behavioural disorders" had already been in use from January 1, 1994, also via a ministerial degree.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] France introduced a clinical addendum to ICD-10 in 1997.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Germany's ICD-10 German Modification (ICD-10-GM) is based on ICD-10-AM.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] ICD-10-GM was developed between 2003 and 2004, by the German Institute for Medical Documentation and Information (DIMDI).
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Since the dissolution of the DIMDI in 2020, the Federal Institute for Drugs and Medical Devices (BfArM) has been responsible for maintaining the ICD-10-GM.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Greece introduced ICD-10 on December 23, 2023.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Hungary introduced the use of ICD-10 from January 1, 1996, via a ministerial decree.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] A Korean modification has existed since 2008.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The Dutch translation of ICD-10 is ICD10-nl, which was created by the WHO-FIC Network in 1994.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The Ministry of Healthcare of the Russian Federation ordered in 1997 to transfer all health organizations to ICD-10.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] ICD-10 was implemented in July 2005 under the auspice of the National ICD-10 Implementation Task Team which is a joint task team between the National Department of Health and the Council for Medical Schemes.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The current Swedish translation of ICD-10 was created in 1997.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] In Switzerland, the German Modification (ICD-10-GM) is used for coding diagnoses.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The Federal Statistical Office (FSO) of Switzerland publishes the ICD-10-GM in French and Italian every two years.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The ICD-10-TM (Thai Modification) is a Thai language version based on the 2016 ICD-10.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] An unusual feature of the index of ICD-10-TM is that it is bilingual, containing both Thai and English trails.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] ICD-10 was first mandated for use in the UK in 1995.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] In 2010 the UK Government made a commitment to update the UK version of ICD-10 every three years.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] On April 1, 2016, following a year's delay, ICD-10 5th Edition replaced the 4th Edition as the mandated diagnostic classification within the UK, and remains the current version for use within the UK.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] For disease reporting, the US utilizes its own national variant of ICD-10 called the ICD-10 Clinical Modification (ICD-10-CM).
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] A procedural classification called ICD-10 Procedure Coding System (ICD-10-PCS) has also been developed for capturing inpatient procedures.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The ICD-10-CM and ICD-10-PCS were developed by the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) and the National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS).
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] There are over 70,000 ICD-10-PCS procedure codes and over 69,000 ICD-10-CM diagnosis codes, compared to about 3,800 procedure codes and roughly 14,000 diagnosis codes found in the previous ICD-9-CM.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] There was much controversy when the transition from the ICD-9-CM to the ICD-10-CM was first announced in the US.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Many providers were concerned about the vast number of codes being added, the complexity of the new coding system, and the costs associated with the transition.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) weighed these concerns against the benefits of having more accurate data collection, clearer documentation of diagnoses and procedures, and more accurate claims processing.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] CMS decided the financial and public health cost associated with continuing to use the ICD-9-CM was too high and mandated the switch to ICD-10-CM.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The deadline for the United States to begin using ICD-10-CM for diagnosis coding and Procedure Coding System ICD-10-PCS for inpatient hospital procedure coding was set at October 1, 2015, a year later than the previous 2014 deadline.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Before the 2014 deadline, the previous deadline had been a year before that on October 1, 2013.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] All HIPAA "covered entities" were required to make the change; a pre-requisite to ICD-10-CM is the adoption of EDI Version 5010 by January 1, 2012.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Enforcement of 5010 transition by the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS), however, was postponed by CMS until March 31, 2012, with the federal agency citing numerous factors, including slow software upgrades.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The implementation of ICD-10-CM has been subject to previous delays.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] In January 2009, the date was pushed back to October 1, 2013, rather than an earlier proposal of October 1, 2011.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Two common complaints in the United States about the ICD-10-CM are 1) the long list of potentially relevant codes for a given condition (such as rheumatoid arthritis) which can be confusing and reduce efficiency and 2) the assigned codes for seldom seen conditions (e.g.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] W55.22XA: Struck by cow, initial encounter; and V91.07XA: Burn due to water-skis on fire, initial encounter).
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The expansion of healthcare delivery systems and changes in global health trends prompted a need for codes with improved clinical accuracy and specificity.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] The alphanumeric coding in ICD-10 is an improvement from ICD-9 which had a limited number of codes and a restrictive structure.
[src:icd-coding/icd-10] Early concerns in the implementation of ICD-10 included the cost and the availability of resources for training healthcare workers and professional coders.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The **ICD-11** is the eleventh revision of the International Classification of Diseases (ICD).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] It replaces the ICD-10 as the global standard for recording health information and causes of death.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD is developed and annually updated by the World Health Organization (WHO).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Development of the ICD-11 started in 2007 and spanned over a decade of work, involving over 300 specialists from 55 countries divided into 30 work groups, with an additional 10,000 proposals from people all over the world.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Following an alpha version in May 2011 and a beta draft in May 2012, a stable version of the ICD-11 was released on 18 June 2018, and officially endorsed by all WHO members during the 72nd World Health Assembly on 28 May 2019.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 is a large ontology consisting of about 85,000 entities, also called classes or nodes.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] An entity can be anything that is relevant to health care.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] It usually represents a disease or a pathogen, but it can also be an isolated symptom or (developmental) anomaly of the body.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] There are also classes for reasons for contact with health services, social circumstances of the patient, and external causes of injury or death.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 is part of the WHO-FIC, a family of medical classifications.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The WHO-FIC contains the Foundation Component, which comprises all entities of the classifications endorsed by the WHO.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The Foundation is the common core from which all classifications are derived.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] For example, the ICD-O is a derivative classification optimized for use in oncology.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The primary derivative of the Foundation is called the ICD-11 MMS, and it is this system that is commonly referred to as simply "the ICD-11".
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] MMS stands for Mortality and Morbidity Statistics.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 is distributed under a Creative Commons BY-ND license.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 officially came into effect on 1 January 2022.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] On 14 February 2023, the WHO reported that 64 countries were "in different stages of ICD-11 implementation".
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In May 2024, they stated that 50 countries were either conducting or expanding implementation pilots, and that 14 countries were actively using the ICD-11.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] According to a *JAMA* article from July 2023, implementation in the United States would at minimum require 4 to 5 years.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 MMS can be viewed online on the WHO's website.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Aside from this, the site offers two maintenance platforms: the ICD-11 Maintenance Platform, and the WHO-FIC Foundation Maintenance Platform.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Users can submit evidence-based suggestions for the improvement of the WHO-FIC, i.e., the ICD-11, the ICF, and the ICHI.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Globally, the first general public hospital to implement ICD-11 was Farwaniya Hospital, in Kuwait.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The WHO Family of International Classifications (WHO-FIC), also called the WHO Family, is a suite of classifications used to describe various aspects of the health care system in a consistent manner, with a standardised terminology.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The abbreviation is variously written with or without a hyphen ("WHO-FIC" or "WHOFIC").
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The WHO-FIC consists of four components: the WHO-FIC Foundation, the Reference Classifications, the Derived Classifications, and the Related Classifications.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The WHO-FIC Foundation, also called the Foundation Component, represents the entire WHO-FIC universe.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] It is a collection of over hundred thousand entities, also called classes or nodes.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Entities are anything relevant to health care.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] They are used to describe diseases, disorders, body parts, bodily functions, reasons for visit, medical procedures, microbes, causes of death, social circumstances of the patient, and much more.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The Foundation Component is a multidimensional collection of entities.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] An entity can have multiple parents and child nodes.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] For example, pneumonia can be categorized as a lung infection, but also as a bacterial or viral infection (i.e. by site or by etiology).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Thus, the node Pneumonia (entity id: 142052508) has two parents: Lung infections (entity id: 915779102) and Certain infectious or parasitic diseases (entity id: 1435254666).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The Pneumonia node in turn has various children, including Bacterial pneumonia (entity id: 1323682030) and Viral pneumonia (entity id: 1024154490).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The Foundation Component is the common core on which all Reference and Derived Classifications are based.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The WHO-FIC contains three Reference Classifications: the ICD-11 MMS (see below), the ICF, and the ICHI.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Derived Classifications are based on the three Reference Classifications, and are usually tailored for a particular specialty.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] For example, the ICD-O is a Derived Classification used in oncology.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Each node of the Foundation has a unique entity id, which remains the same in all Reference and Derived Classifications, guaranteeing consistency.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Related Classifications are complementary, and cover specialty areas not covered elsewhere in the WHO-FIC.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] For example, the International Classification of Nursing Practice (ICNP), draws on terms from the Foundation Component, but also uses terms specific for nursing not found in the Foundation.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] A classification can be represented as a tabular list, which is a "flat" hierarchical tree of categories.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In this tree, all entities can only have a single parent, and therefore must be mutually exclusive of each other.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Such a classification is also called a linearization.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 MMS is the main Reference Classification of the WHO-FIC, and the primary linearization of the Foundation Component.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 MMS is commonly referred to as simply "the ICD-11".
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The "MMS" part was added to differentiate the ICD-11 entities in the Foundation from those in the Classification.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 MMS does not contain all classes from the Foundation ICD-11, and also adds some classes from the ICF.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The abbreviation is variously written with or without a hyphen between 11 and MMS ("ICD-11 MMS" or "ICD-11-MMS").
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 MMS consists of approximately 85,000 entities.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Entities can be chapters, blocks or categories.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] A chapter is a top level entity of the hierarchy; the MMS contains 28 of them (see Chapters section below).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] A block is used to group related categories or blocks together.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] A category can be anything that is relevant to health care.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Every category has a unique, alphanumeric code called an ICD-11 code, or just ICD code.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Chapters and blocks never have ICD-11 codes, and therefore cannot be diagnosed.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] An ICD-11 code is not the same as an entity id.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 MMS takes the form of a "flat" hierarchical tree.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] As aforementioned, the entities in this linearization can only have a single parent, and therefore must be mutually exclusive of each other.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] To make up for this limitation, the hierarchy of the MMS contains gray nodes.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] These nodes appear as children in the hierarchy, but actually have a different parent node.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] They originally belong to a different block or chapter, but are also listed elsewhere because of overlap.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] For example, Pneumonia (CA40) has two parents in the Foundation: "Lung infections" (site) and "Certain infectious or parasitic diseases" (etiology).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the MMS, Pneumonia is categorized in the "Lung infections", with a gray node in "Certain infectious or parasitic diseases".
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The same goes for injuries, poisonings, neoplasms, and developmental anomalies, which can occur in almost any part of the body.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] They each have their own chapters, but their categories also have gray nodes in the chapters of the organs they affect.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] For instance, the blood cancers, including all forms of leukemia, are in the "Neoplasms" chapter, but they are also displayed as gray nodes in the chapter "Diseases of the blood or blood-forming organs".
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 MMS also contains residual categories, or residual nodes.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] These are the "Other specified" and "Unspecified" categories.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The former can be used to code conditions that do not fit with any of the more specific MMS entities, the latter can be used when necessary information may not be available in the source documentation.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 Reference Guide advises that health care workers always aim to include the most specific level of detail possible, either with one code or multiple codes.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the ICD-11 Browser, residual nodes are displayed in a maroon color.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Residual categories are not in the Foundation, and therefore do not have an entity ID.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Thus, in the MMS, they are the only categories with derivative entity IDs: their IDs are the same as their parent nodes, with "/other" or "/unspecified" tagged at the end.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Their ICD codes always end with Y for "Other specified" categories, or Z for "Unspecified" categories (e.g.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] These are terms or conditions which are judged important or commonly used in relation to that code.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] ICD-11 is a digital-first classification that supports straightforward single-code assignment for routine use.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Where additional detail is required, post-coordination allows code clusters (stem plus extension codes or also stem plus stem codes with or without extension codes) to be created; the Browser and Coding Tool guide users through these combinations.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] ICD-11 provides a REST and FHIR-compliant multilingual API and embeds a web-based Coding Tool in the Browser for everyday coding.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Tooling includes search, clustering of stem and extension codes, and NLP-assisted features to reduce manual lookup and improve accuracy.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] ICD-11 with all its tools can be downloaded and used on local computers in Docker, or as a Windows or Linux server.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Code samples facilitate integration in existing software.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Documentation on the above, the ICD API and some additional tools for integration into third-party applications can be found at the ICD API home page.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The WHO has released spreadsheets that can be used to link and convert ICD-10 codes to those of the ICD-11.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] They can be downloaded from the ICD-11 MMS browser.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Since 2017, WHO and SNOMED International are exploring ways of funding and governance in relation to formulating a bidirectional map between SNOMED CT and ICD-11.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] No deadlines for agreements, start of the work, or availability of any map has been communicated as of 2025.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 Foundation, and consequently the MMS, are updated annually, similarly to the ICD-10.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The first stable version was released on 18 June 2018.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] On 16 February 2026, the Foundation and the MMS received its eight update (and ninth stable release overall).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Below is a table of all chapters of the ICD-11 MMS, the primary linearization of the Foundation Component.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Unlike the ICD-10 codes, the ICD-11 MMS codes never contain the letters I or O, to prevent confusion with the numbers 1 and 0.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Below is a summary of notable changes in the ICD-11 MMS compared to the ICD-10.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 MMS features a more flexible coding structure.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the ICD-10, every code starts with a letter, followed by a two digit number (e.g.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] P35), creating 99 slots, excluding subcategories and blocks.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] This proved enough for most chapters, but four are so voluminous that their categories span multiple letters: Chapter I (A00–B99), Chapter II (C00.0–D48.9), Chapter XIX (S00–T98), and Chapter XX (V01–Y98).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the ICD-11 MMS, there is a single first character for every chapter.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The codes of the first nine chapters begin with the numbers 1 to 9, while the next nineteen chapters start with the letters A to X.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The letters I and O are not used, to prevent confusion with the numbers 1 and 0.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The chapter character is then followed by a letter, a number, and a fourth character that starts as a number (0–9, e.g.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] KA80) and may then continue as a letter (A–Z, e.g.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The WHO opted for a forced number as the third character to prevent the spelling of "undesirable words".
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the ICD-10, each entity within a chapter either has a code (e.g.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the ICD-11 MMS, blocks never have codes, and not every entity necessarily has a code, although each entity does have a unique id.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the ICD-10, the next level of the hierarchy is indicated in the code by a dot and a single number (e.g.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] This is the lowest available level in the ICD-10 hierarchy, causing an artificial limitation of 10 subcategories per code (.0 to .9).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the ICD-11 MMS, this limitation no longer exists: after 0–9, the list may continue with A–Z (e.g.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Then, following the first character after the dot, a second character may be used in the next level of the hierarchy (e.g.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] This level is currently the lowest appearing in the MMS.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The large amount of unused coding space in the MMS allows for updates to be made without having to change the other categories, ensuring that codes remain stable.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The third chapter of the ICD-10, "Diseases of the blood and blood-forming organs and certain disorders involving the immune mechanism", has been split in two: "Diseases of the blood or blood-forming organs" (chapter 3) and "Diseases of the immune system" (chapter 4).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The other new chapters are "Sleep-wake disorders" (chapter 7), "Conditions related to sexual health" (chapter 17, see section), and "Supplementary Chapter Traditional Medicine Conditions - Module I" (chapter 26, see section).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Following an extensive, years-long revision process involving nearly 15,000 clinicians from 155 countries, the WHO developed the **ICD-11 CDDG** (Clinical Descriptions and Diagnostic Guidelines), later renamed the **ICD-11 CDDR** (Clinical Descriptions and Diagnostic Requirements).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The CDDR is a comprehensive diagnostic manual for identifying and measuring mental illnesses with a uniform terminology, similar to the DSM-5.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 CDDR was developed around the same time as the DSM-5, and the work groups of both projects regularly met to discuss their efforts.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The CDDR and the DSM-5 are similar, but not identical.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 CDDR is the successor to the ICD-10 CDDG, which was first released in 1992 and was also known as the "Blue Book".
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The CDDR is integrated into the ICD-11, and can be viewed in the ICD-11 Browser.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] On 8 March 2024, the CDDR was also released in e-book form – it can be downloaded for free from the WHO's website.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 classification of personality disorders differs substantially from the one in the previous edition, ICD-10; all distinct PDs have been merged into one: *personality disorder*, which can be coded as *mild*, *moderate*, *severe*, or *severity unspecified*.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] There is also an additional category called *personality difficulty*, which can be used to describe personality traits that are problematic, but do not meet the diagnostic criteria for a PD.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] A personality disorder or difficulty can be specified by one or more of the following *prominent personality traits or patterns*: Negative affectivity, Detachment, Dissociality, Disinhibition, and Anankastia.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In addition to the traits, a *Borderline pattern –* similar in nature to borderline personality disorder – may be specified.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Gaming disorder (6C51) has been newly added to the ICD-11, and placed in the group "Disorders due to addictive behaviours", alongside Gambling disorder (6C50).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The latter was called Pathological gambling (F63.0) in the ICD-10.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Aside from Gaming disorder, the ICD-11 also features Hazardous gaming (QE22), an ancillary category that can be used to identify problematic gaming which does not rise to the level of a disorder.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Although a majority of scholars supported the inclusion of Gaming disorder (GD), a significant number did not.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Rooij *et al.* questioned if what was called "gaming disorder" is in fact a coping strategy for underlying problems, such as depression, social anxiety, or ADHD.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] They also asserted moral panic, fueled by sensational media stories, and stated that the category could be stigmatizing people who are simply engaging in a very immersive hobby.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Bean *et al.* wrote that the GD category caters to false stereotypes of gamers as physically unfit and socially awkward, and that most gamers have no problems balancing their expected social roles outside games with those inside.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In support of the GD category, Lee *et al.* agreed that there were major limitations of the existing research, but that this actually necessitates a standardized set of criteria, which would benefit studies more than self-developed instruments for evaluating problematic gaming.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Saunders *et al.* argued that gaming addiction should be in the ICD-11 just as much as gambling addiction and substance addiction, citing functional neuroimaging studies which show similar brain regions being activated, and psychological studies which show similar antecedents (risk factors).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Király and Demetrovics did not believe that a GD category would lock research into a confirmatory approach, noting that the ICD is regularly revised and characterized by permanent change.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] They wrote that moral panic around gamers does indeed exist, but that this is not caused by a formal diagnosis.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Rumpf *et al.* noted that stigmatization is a risk not specific to GD alone.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] They agreed that GD could be a coping strategy for an underlying disorder, but that in this debate, "comorbidity is more often the rule than the exception".
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] For example, a person can have an alcohol dependence due to PTSD.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In clinical practice, *both* disorders need to be diagnosed and treated.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Rumpf *et al.* also warned that the lack of a GD category might jeopardize insurance reimbursement of treatments.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The DSM-5 (2013) features a similar category called Internet Gaming Disorder (IGD).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] However, due to the controversy over its definition and inclusion, it is not included in its main body of mental diagnoses, but in the additional chapter "Conditions for Further Study".
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Disorders in this chapter are meant to encourage research and are not intended for clinical use.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In May 2019, a number of media incorrectly reported that burn-out was newly added to the ICD-11.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In reality, burn-out is also in the ICD-10 (Z73.0), albeit with a short, one-sentence definition only.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 features a longer summary, and specifically notes that the category should only be used in an occupational context.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Furthermore, it should only be applied when mood disorders (6A60–6A8Z), Disorders specifically associated with stress (6B40–6B4Z), and Anxiety or fear-related disorders (6B00–6B0Z) have been ruled out.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] As with the ICD-10, burn-out is not in the mental disorders chapter of the ICD-11, but in the chapter "Factors influencing health status or contact with health services", where it is coded QD85.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In response to media attention over its inclusion, the WHO emphasized that the ICD-11 does not define burn-out as a mental disorder or a disease, but as an occupational phenomenon that undermines a person's well-being in the workplace.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Conditions related to sexual health is a new chapter in the ICD-11.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The WHO decided to put the sexual disorders in a separate chapter due to "the outdated mind/body split".
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] A number of ICD-10 categories, including sex disorders, were based on a Cartesian separation of "organic" (physical) and "non-organic" (mental) conditions.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] As such, the sexual dysfunctions that were considered non-organic were included in the mental disorder chapter, while those that were considered organic were for the most part listed in the chapter on diseases of the genitourinary system.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the ICD-11, the brain and the body are seen as an integrate whole, with sexual dysfunctions considered to involve an interaction between physical and psychological factors.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Thus, the organic/non-organic distinction was abolished.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Regarding general sexual dysfunction, the ICD-10 has three main categories: Lack or loss of sexual desire (F52.0), Sexual aversion and lack of sexual enjoyment (F52.1), and Failure of genital response (F52.2).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 replaces these with two main categories: Hypoactive sexual desire dysfunction (HA00) and Sexual arousal dysfunction (HA01).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The latter has two subcategories: Female sexual arousal dysfunction (HA01.0) and Male erectile dysfunction (HA01.1).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The difference between Hypoactive sexual desire dysfunction and Sexual arousal dysfunction is that in the former, there is a reduced or absent desire for sexual activity.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the latter, there is insufficient physical and emotional response to sexual activity, even though there still is a *desire* to engage in satisfying sex.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The WHO acknowledged that there is an overlap between desire and arousal, but they are not the same.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Management should focus on their distinct features.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-10 contains the categories Vaginismus (N94.2), Nonorganic vaginismus (F52.5), Dyspareunia (N94.1), and Nonorganic dyspareunia (F52.6).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] As the WHO aimed to steer away from the aforementioned "outdated mind/body split", the organic and nonorganic disorders were merged.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Vaginismus has been reclassified as Sexual pain-penetration disorder (HA20).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] A related condition is Vulvodynia, which is in the ICD-9 (625.7), but not in the ICD-10.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] It has been re-added to the ICD-11 (GA34.02).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Sexual dysfunctions and Sexual pain-penetration disorder can be coded alongside a temporal qualifier, "lifelong" or "acquired", and a situational qualifier, "general" or "situational".
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Furthermore, the ICD-11 offers five aetiological qualifiers, or "Associated with..." categories, to further specify the diagnosis.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] For example, a woman who experiences sexual problems due to adverse effects of an SSRI antidepressant may be diagnosed with "Female sexual arousal dysfunction, acquired, generalised" (HA01.02) combined with "Associated with use of psychoactive substance or medication" (HA40.2).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Excessive sexual drive (F52.7) from the ICD-10 has been reclassified as Compulsive sexual behaviour disorder (CSBD, 6C72) and listed under Impulse control disorders.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The WHO was unwilling to overpathologize sexual behaviour, stating that having a high sexual drive is not necessarily a disorder, so long as these people do not exhibit impaired control over their behavior, significant distress, or impairment in functioning.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Kraus *et al.* noted that several people self-identify as "sex addicts", but on closer examination do not actually exhibit the clinical characteristics of a sexual disorder, although they may have other mental health problems, such as anxiety or depression.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Experiencing shame and guilt about sex is not a reliable indicator of a sex disorder, Kraus *et al.* stated.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] There was debate on whether CSBD should be considered a (behavioral) addiction.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] It has been claimed that neuroimaging shows overlap between compulsive sexual behavior and substance-use disorder through common neurotransmitter systems.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Nonetheless, it was ultimately decided to place the disorder in the Impulse control disorders group.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Paraphilic disorders, called Disorders of sexual preference in the ICD-10, have remained in the mental disorders chapter, although they have gray nodes in the sexual health chapter.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-10 categories Fetishism (F65.0) and Fetishistic transvestism (F65.1) were removed because, if they do not cause distress or harm, they are not considered mental disorders.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Frotteuristic disorder (6D34) has been newly added.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Gender dysphoria of transgender people is called Gender incongruence in the ICD-11.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the ICD-10, the group Gender identity disorders (F64) consisted of three main categories: Transsexualism (F64.0), Dual-role transvestism (F64.1), and Gender identity disorder of childhood (F64.2).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the ICD-11, Dual-role transvestism was deleted due to a lack of public health or clinical relevance.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Transsexualism was renamed Gender incongruence of adolescence or adulthood (HA60), and Gender identity disorder of childhood was renamed Gender incongruence of childhood (HA61).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the ICD-10, the Gender identity disorders were placed in the mental disorders chapter, following what was customary at the time.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Throughout the 20th century, both the ICD and the DSM approached transgender health from a psychopathological position, as transgender identity presents a discrepancy between someone's assigned sex and their gender identity.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Since this may cause mental distress, it was consequently considered a mental disorder, with distress or discomfort being a core diagnostic feature.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In the 2000s and 2010s, this notion became increasingly challenged, as the idea of viewing transgender people as having a mental disorder was believed by some to be stigmatizing.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] It has been suggested that distress and dysfunction among transgender people should be more appropriately viewed as the result of social rejection, discrimination, and violence toward individuals with gender variant appearance and behavior.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Studies have shown transgender people to be at higher risk of developing mental health problems than other populations, but that health services aimed at transgender people are often insufficient or nonexistent.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Since an official ICD code is usually needed to gain access to and reimbursement for gender-affirming care, the WHO found it ill-advised to remove transgender health from the ICD-11 altogether.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] It was therefore decided to transpose the concept from the mental disorders chapter to the new sexual health chapter.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The group related to coding antimicrobial resistance has been significantly expanded in the ICD-11 compared to the ICD-10.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Also, the ICD-11 codes are more closely in line with the WHO's Global Antimicrobial Resistance Surveillance System (GLASS).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Launched in October 2015, this project aims to track the growing worldwide resistance of malicious microbes (viruses, bacteria, fungi, and protozoa) against medication.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] "Supplementary Chapter Traditional Medicine Conditions" is an additional chapter in the ICD-11, featuring concepts that are considered part of traditional medicine (TM).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] It initially consisted of one module, TM1.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] This module contains concepts that originated in traditional Chinese medicine (TCM), also having long histories of development and use in Japan (Kampo), Korea (TKM), and Vietnam (TVM).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In February 2025, a second module was added, TM2.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] This module features concepts related to Ayurveda, Siddha, and Unani.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] A third module, covering homeopathy, is planned, as well as a fourth module covering "other TM systems with independent diagnostic conditions".
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] As of June 2026, TM3 and TM4 have yet to be released.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Medical procedures that are labeled "traditional" are used all over the world.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] A 2008 survey by the WHO found that, in some Asian and African countries, as much as 80% of the population rely on traditional medicine for primary health care.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In many developed countries, 70% to 80% of the population had used a form of alternative medicine at some point, such as acupuncture.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Even though a number of countries created national classifications of TM, an international standardized system was missing.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] This complicated data collection, making it more difficult for the WHO to comprehensively monitor the usage, safety, efficacy, and costs of TM-practices.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] During the 1970s, TM became a topic of increasing interest in Europe and North America.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] On 19 May 1977, the WHO passed a resolution approving the initiation of TM-related training and research, which is considered the official beginning of the WHO's endorsement of TM.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The declaration of Alma-Ata in 1978 mentioned the role of traditional practitioners in health care.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In 1984, the WHO released the first version of the *Standard Acupuncture Nomenclature*.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The *WHO Traditional Medicine Strategy 2002–2005* outlined a plan to, among other things, integrate TM with national health care systems, expand the knowledge base about TM, and enhance its safety, efficacy, and quality.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The *WHO International Standard Terminologies on Traditional Medicine in the Western Pacific Region* (2007), or simply IST, defines terms related to qi, acupuncture, moxibustion, cupping, Chinese herbology, and other concepts within traditional Chinese medicine (TCM).
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Elaborating on the IST, the WHO developed the International Classification of Traditional Medicine (ICTM), the contents of which form Chapter 26 of the ICD-11.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The decision to include TM in the ICD-11 has been criticized, because it is often alleged to be pseudoscience.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Editorials by *Nature* and *Scientific American* admitted that some TM techniques and herbs have shown effectiveness or potential, but that others are pointless, or even outright harmful.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] They wrote that the inclusion of the TM-chapter is at odds with the scientific, evidence-based methods usually employed by the WHO.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] Both editorials accused the government of China of pushing the WHO to incorporate traditional Chinese medicine, a global, billion-dollar market in which China plays a leading role.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] In *Forbes*, Steven Salzberg wrote: "There's no legitimate reason to use terms such as "Chinese" medicine, or American, Italian, Spanish, Indian, or [insert your favorite nationality] medicine.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] There's just medicine – if a treatment works, then it's medicine.
[src:icd-coding/icd-11] The ICD-11 Reference Guide recommends the TM-codes "be used in conjunction with the Western Medicine concepts of ICD-11 chapters 1-25".
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] It exists currently in its eleventh revision ICD-11 and it is notably different in detail and technology from all previous revisions of ICD.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The ICD is maintained by the World Health Organization (WHO), which is the directing and coordinating authority for health within the United Nations System.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The ICD provides a standardized framework for recording causes of illness and death, interoperability, comparing health data across countries and time periods, supporting reimbursement and resource allocation, and feeding automated decision support in clinical and public health settings.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] It maps health conditions to corresponding generic categories together with specific variations, each assigned a designated code.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Its consistent application underpins international comparability in the collection, processing, and analysis of health statistics — a foundation for evidence-based health policy at both national and global levels.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The ICD is published by the WHO and used worldwide for morbidity and mortality recording and statistics, reimbursement systems, and automated decision support in health care.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The ICD is a core system for healthcare-related issues of the WHO Family of International Classifications (WHO-FIC).
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The ICD-11, as it is known, was adopted by WHO's World Health Assembly (WHA) on 25 May 2019 and officially came into effect on 1 January 2022.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] On 11 February 2022, the WHO stated that 35 countries were using the ICD-11.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] As of July 2025, 132 WHO member states were at various stages of ICD-11 implementation.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The title of the ICD is formally the International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health Problems; the original title, the International Classification of Diseases, is still the informal name by which the ICD is usually known.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] In the United States and some other countries, the *Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders* (DSM) is preferred when classifying mental disorders for certain purposes.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The ICD is currently the most widely used statistical classification system for diseases in the world.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] In addition, some countries—including Australia, Canada, and the United States—have developed their own adaptations of ICD, with more procedure codes for classification of operative or diagnostic procedures.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] In 1860, during the international statistical congress held in London, Florence Nightingale made a proposal that was to result in the development of the first model of systematic collection of hospital data.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] In 1893, a French physician, Jacques Bertillon, introduced the *Bertillon Classification of Causes of Death* at a congress of the International Statistical Institute (ISI) in Chicago.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] A number of countries adopted Bertillon's system, which was based on the principle of distinguishing between general diseases and those localized to a particular organ or anatomical site, as used by the City of Paris for classifying deaths.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Subsequent revisions represented a synthesis of English, German, and Swiss classifications, expanding from the original 44 titles to 161 titles.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] In 1898, the American Public Health Association (APHA) recommended that the registrars of Canada, Mexico, and the United States also adopt it.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The APHA also recommended revising the system every 10 years to ensure the system remained current with medical practice advances.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] As a result, the first international conference to revise the *International Classification of Causes of Death* (ICD) took place in 1900, with revisions occurring every ten years thereafter.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] At that time, the classification system was contained in one book, which included an Alphabetic Index as well as a Tabular List.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The book was small compared with current coding texts.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The revisions that followed contained minor changes.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Responsibility for ICD revisions fell to the Mixed Commission, a group composed of representatives from the ISI and the Health Organization of the League of Nations.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] In 1948, the WHO assumed responsibility for preparing and publishing the revisions to the ICD every ten years.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The ICD-6, published in 1949, was the first to be shaped to become suitable for morbidity reporting.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Accordingly, the name changed from "International List of Causes of Death" to the "International Statistical Classification of Diseases, Injuries and Causes of Death" (ICD).
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The combined code section for injuries and their associated accidents was split into two, a chapter for injuries, and a chapter for their external causes.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] With use for morbidity there was a need for coding mental conditions, and for the first time a section on mental disorders was added.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The International Conference for the Seventh Revision of the International Classification of Diseases was held in Paris under the auspices of WHO in February 1955.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] In accordance with a recommendation of the WHO Expert Committee on Health Statistics, this revision was limited to essential changes and amendments of errors and inconsistencies.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The 8th Revision Conference convened by WHO met in Geneva, from 6 to 12 July 1965.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] This revision was more radical than the Seventh but left unchanged the basic structure of the Classification and the general philosophy of classifying diseases, whenever possible, according to their etiology rather than a particular manifestation.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] During the years that the Seventh and Eighth Revisions of the ICD were in force, the use of the ICD for indexing hospital medical records increased rapidly and some countries prepared national adaptations which provided the additional detail needed for this application of the ICD.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] In the US, a group of consultants was asked to study the ICD-8 for its applicability to various users in the United States.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] This group recommended that further detail be provided for coding hospital and morbidity data.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The American Hospital Association's "Advisory Committee to the Central Office on ICDA" developed the needed adaptation proposals, resulting in the publication of the International Classification of Diseases, Adapted (ICDA).
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] In 1968, the United States Public Health Service published the International Classification of Diseases, Adapted, 8th Revision for use in the United States (ICDA-8).
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Beginning in 1968, ICDA-8 served as the basis for coding diagnostic data for both official morbidity and mortality statistics in the United States.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The International Conference for the Ninth Revision of the International Statistical Classification of Diseases, Injuries, and Causes of Death, convened by WHO, met in Geneva from 30 September to 6 October 1975.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] In the discussions leading up to the conference, it had originally been intended that there should be little change other than updating of the classification.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] This was mainly because of the expense of adapting data processing systems each time the classification was revised.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] There had been an enormous growth of interest in the ICD and ways had to be found of responding to this, partly by modifying the classification itself and partly by introducing special coding provisions.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] A number of representations were made by specialist bodies which had become interested in using the ICD for their own statistics.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] At the other end of the scale, there were representations from countries and areas where a detailed and sophisticated classification was irrelevant, but which nevertheless needed a classification based on the ICD in order to assess their progress in health care and in the control of disease.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] A field test with a bi-axial classification approach—one axis (criterion) for anatomy, with another for etiology—showed the impracticability of such approach for routine use.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The final proposals presented to and accepted by the Conference in 1978 retained the basic structure of the ICD, although with much additional detail at the level of the four digit subcategories, and some optional five digit subdivisions.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] For the benefit of users not requiring such detail, care was taken to ensure that the categories at the three digit level were appropriate.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] This system became known as the 'dagger and asterisk system' and is retained in the Tenth Revision.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] It was eventually replaced by ICD-10, the version currently in use by the WHO and most countries.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Given the widespread expansion in the tenth revision, it is not possible to convert ICD-9 data sets directly into ICD-10 data sets, although some tools are available to help guide users.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Publication of ICD-9 without IP restrictions in a world with evolving electronic data systems led to a range of products based on ICD-9, such as MeDRA or the Read directory.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] When ICD-9 was published by the World Health Organization (WHO), the International Classification of Procedures in Medicine (ICPM) was also developed (1975) and published (1978).
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The ICPM surgical procedures fascicle was originally created by the United States, based on its adaptations of ICD (called ICDA), which had contained a procedure classification since 1962.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] ICPM is published separately from the ICD disease classification as a series of supplementary documents called fascicles (bundles or groups of items).
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Each fascicle contains a classification of modes of laboratory, radiology, surgery, therapy, and other diagnostic procedures.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Many countries have adapted and translated the ICPM in parts or as a whole and are using it with amendments since then.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The ICD-9-CM is based on the ICD-9 but provides for additional morbidity detail.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The NCHS and the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services are the US governmental agencies responsible for overseeing all changes and modifications to the ICD-9-CM.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Work on ICD-10 began in 1983, and the new revision was endorsed by the Forty-third World Health Assembly in May 1990.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The latest version came into effect in WHO Member States starting on 1 January 1993.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The classification system allows more than 55,000 different codes and permits tracking of many new diagnoses and procedures, a significant expansion on the 17,000 codes available in ICD-9.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Adoption was relatively swift in most of the world.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Several materials are made available online by WHO to facilitate its use, including manuals for both general use (*ICD-10 Volume 2*) and Chapter V specifically (*The ICD-10 Classification of Mental and Behavioural Disorders*), training guidelines, a browser, and files for download.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Some countries have adapted the international standard, such as the "ICD-10-AM" published in Australia in 1998 (also used in New Zealand), and the "ICD-10-CA" introduced in Canada in 2000.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Adoption of ICD-10-CM was slow in the United States.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Since 1979, the US had required ICD-9-CM codes for Medicare and Medicaid claims, and most of the rest of the American medical industry followed suit.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] On 1 January 1999 the ICD-10 (without clinical extensions) was adopted for reporting mortality, but ICD-9-CM was still used for morbidity.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] On 21 August 2008, the US Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) proposed new code sets to be used for reporting diagnoses and procedures on health care transactions.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Under the proposal, the ICD-9-CM code sets would be replaced with the ICD-10-CM code sets, effective 1 October 2013.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] On 17 April 2012 the Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) published a proposed rule that would delay, from 1 October 2013 to 1 October 2014, the compliance date for the ICD-10-CM and PCS.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Once again, Congress delayed implementation date to 1 October 2015, after it was inserted into "Doc Fix" Bill without debate over objections of many.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] ICD-10-CA is a clinical modification of ICD-10 developed by the Canadian Institute for Health Information for morbidity classification in Canada.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] ICD-10-CA applies beyond acute hospital care, and includes conditions and situations that are not diseases but represent risk factors to health, such as occupational and environmental factors, lifestyle and psycho-social circumstances.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The eleventh revision of the International Classification of Diseases, or the ICD-11, is almost five times as big as the ICD-10.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] It was created following a decade of development involving over 300 specialists from 55 countries.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Following an alpha version in May 2011 and a beta draft in May 2012, a stable version of the ICD-11 was released on 18 June 2018, and officially endorsed by all WHO members during the 72nd World Health Assembly on 25 May 2019.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] For the ICD-11, the WHO decided to differentiate between the core of the system and its derived specialty versions, such as the ICD-O for oncology.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] As such, the collection of all ICD entities is called the Foundation Component.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] From this common core, subsets can be derived.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The primary derivative of the Foundation is called the ICD-11 MMS, and it is this system that is commonly referred to and recognized as "the ICD-11".
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] ICD-11 comes with an implementation package that includes transition tables from and to ICD-10, a translation tool, a coding tool, web-services, the ICD-11 CDDR (a DSM-like manual for Chapter 06), training material, and more.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] All tools are accessible after self-registration from the Maintenance Platform.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The ICD-11 *officially* came into effect on 1 January 2022, although the WHO admitted that "not many countries are likely to adapt that quickly".
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] In the United States, the advisory body of the Secretary of Health and Human Services in 2019 gave an expected release year of 2025.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] However by April 2024, with little progress towards ICD-11 adoption having been made, the advisory body was recommending that the Secretary urgently appoint a central office or agency to take responsibility for co-ordinating the adoption of ICD-11 in the United States.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] In China, the National Health Commission endorsed the transition to ICD-11 in 2018, and in 2023 a national pilot of the ICD-11 morbidity coding was carried out.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The US Public Health Service later published the *Eighth Revision, International Classification of Diseases, Adapted for Use in the United States*, commonly referred to as ICDA-8, for official national morbidity and mortality statistics.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] This was followed by the *ICD, 9th Revision, Clinical Modification*, known as ICD-9-CM, published by the US Department of Health and Human Services and used by hospitals and other healthcare facilities to better describe the clinical picture of the patient.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The diagnosis component of ICD-9-CM is completely consistent with ICD-9 codes, and remains the data standard for reporting morbidity.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] National adaptations of the ICD-10 progressed to incorporate both clinical code (ICD-10-CM) and procedure code (ICD-10-PCS) with the revisions completed in 2003.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] In 2009, the US Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services announced that it would begin using ICD-10 on April 1, 2010, with full compliance by all involved parties by 2013.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] However, the US extended the deadline twice and did not formally require transitioning to ICD-10-CM (for most clinical encounters) until October 1, 2015.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Cause of death on United States death certificates, statistically compiled by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), are coded in the ICD, which does not include codes for human and system factors commonly called medical errors.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] Some EU countries use the ICD to compute the maximum Abbreviated Injury Scale for traffic statistics.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The various ICD editions include sections that classify mental and behavioural disorders.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The *ICD-10 Classification of Mental and Behavioural Disorders: Clinical Descriptions and Diagnostic Guidelines* – also known as the "blue book" – is derived from Chapter V of ICD-10 and gives the diagnostic criteria for the conditions listed at each category therein.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The blue book was developed separately to, but coexists with, the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM) of the American Psychiatric Association—though both seek to use the same diagnostic classifications.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] A survey of psychiatrists in 66 countries comparing use of the ICD-10 and DSM-IV found that the former was more often used for clinical diagnosis while the latter was more valued for research.
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] As part of the development of the ICD-11, WHO established an "International Advisory Group" to guide what would become the chapter on "Mental, behavioural or neurodevelopmental disorders".
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The working group proposed that ICD-11 should declassify the categories within ICD-10 at "F66 Psychological and behavioural disorders that are associated with sexual development and orientation".
[src:icd-coding/international-classification-of-diseases] The ICD is actually the official system for the US, although many mental health professionals do not realize this due to the dominance of the DSM.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Because the U.S. has a mix of government-sponsored and private healthcare, health insurance companies—otherwise known as payors—are the primary entity to which claims are billed for physician reimbursement.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The process begins when a physician documents a patient's visit, including the diagnoses, treatments, and prescribed medications or recommended procedures.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] This information is translated into standardized codes through medical coding, using the appropriate coding systems such as ICD-10-CM and Current Procedural Terminology (CPT).
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] A medical biller then takes the coded information, combined with the patient's insurance details, and forms a claim that is submitted to the payors.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Payors evaluate claims by verifying the patient's insurance details, medical necessity of the recommended medical management plan, and adherence to insurance policy guidelines.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The payor returns the claim back to the medical biller and the biller evaluates how much of the bill the patient owes, after insurance is taken out.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] If the claim is approved, the payor processes payment, either reimbursing the physician directly or the patient.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Claims that are denied or underpaid may require follow-up, appeals, or adjustments by the medical billing department.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Accurate medical billing demands proficiency in coding and billing standards, a thorough understanding of insurance policies, and attention to detail to ensure timely and accurate reimbursement.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] While certification is not legally required to become a medical biller, professional credentials such as the Certified Medical Reimbursement Specialist (CMRS), Registered Health Information Administrator (RHIA), or Certified Professional Biller (CPB) can enhance employment prospects.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Training programs, ranging from certificates to associate degrees, are offered at many community colleges, and advanced roles may require cross-training in medical coding, auditing, or healthcare information management.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Medical billing practices vary across states and healthcare settings, influenced by federal regulations, state laws, and payor-specific requirements.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Despite these variations, the fundamental goal remains consistent: to streamline the financial transactions between physicians and payors, ensuring access to care and financial sustainability for physicians.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] In 18th-century England, physicians were not legally permitted to charge fees for their services or take legal action to collect payments.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Instead, patients would offer honoraria, which were voluntary payments inspired by what was believed to be a Roman custom.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] This honorarium rule applied only to non-surgeon physicians.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Meanwhile, surgery was treated as a public calling, allowing courts to cap surgeons' fees to reasonable amounts.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The honorarium rule for non-surgeon physicians and the public calling status for surgeons highlighted the unique, non-commercial constraints on medical professionals at the time.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] These constraints further emphasized professionalism over commerce, distinguishing these professions from regular businesses.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] In the 19th century, the American colonies abandoned the English honorarium and public calling principles.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Instead, physicians could use standard contract and commercial law to set and collect fees.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Unlike in England, U.S. courts viewed medical services like goods with fixed prices, allowing physicians to sue for outstanding payments and freely set terms, independent of obligations tied to public service.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Before the spread of health insurance, doctors charged patients according to what they thought each patient could afford.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] This practice was known as sliding fees and became a legal rule in the 20th century in the U.S.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Eventually, changing economic conditions and the introduction of health insurance in the mid-20th century ushered an end to the sliding scale.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Health insurance became a conduit for billing, and it standardized fees by negotiating fee schedules, eliminating additional charges, and restricting discounts that the sliding scale offered.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] For several decades, medical billing was done almost entirely on paper.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] However, with the advent of medical practice management software, also known as health information systems, it has become possible to efficiently manage large amounts of claims.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Many software companies have arisen to provide medical billing software to this particularly lucrative segment of the market.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Several companies also offer full portal solutions through their web interfaces, which negates the cost of individually licensed software packages.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Due to the rapidly changing requirements by U.S. health insurance companies, several aspects of medical billing and medical office management have created the necessity for specialized training.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Medical office personnel may obtain certification through various institutions who may provide a variety of specialized education and in some cases award a certification credential to reflect professional status.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Visiting a doctor might seem like a straightforward one-on-one interaction, but it is actually part of a much larger and more complex system involving information exchange and payment processing.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] While an insured patient typically interacts only with a healthcare provider during a visit, the encounter is part of a three-party system.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The first party in this system is the patient.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The second is the healthcare provider, a term that encompasses not only physicians but also hospitals, physical therapists, emergency rooms, outpatient facilities, and other entities delivering medical services.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The third and final party is the payor, typically an insurance company, which facilitates reimbursement for the services rendered.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Medical billing involves creating invoices for services rendered to patients, a process known as the billing cycle or Revenue Cycle Management (RCM).
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] RCM encompasses the entire revenue collection process for a healthcare facility, beginning with the design of the RCM workflow.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] This cycle can take anywhere from a few days to several months, often requiring multiple interactions before achieving resolution.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The relationship between healthcare providers and insurance companies resembles that of a vendor and subcontractor: healthcare providers contract with insurers to deliver services to covered patients.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The process begins when a patient schedules an appointment.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] For new patients, this involves gathering essential information, including their medical history, insurance details, and personal data.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] For returning patients, the focus is on updating records with the latest reason for the visit and any changes to their personal or insurance information.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] This foundational step ensures the practice has accurate and up-to-date records for billing and care coordination.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Once the patient is registered, the next step is to identify which treatments or services their insurance plan will cover.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Insurance policies often include specific guidelines regarding covered procedures and exclusions, and these rules can change annually.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] To avoid billing complications, the healthcare provider must stay informed about the most recent coverage requirements for each insurance plan.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] This is where medical billing departs from medical coding.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Medical coders are responsible for this step and they rely on two standardized coding systems to document and classify the services provided, which will eventually be put into a bill by medical billers.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] ICD codes: Developed by the World Health Organization, the International Classification of Diseases (ICD) codes describe the conditions or symptoms being evaluated or treated.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The current version, ICD-10, will transition to ICD-11 in 2025, requiring updated coding practices.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] CPT codes: Created by the American Medical Association (AMA), Current Procedural Terminology (CPT) codes correspond to the procedures or treatments performed by the healthcare provider.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] These codes are essential for accurately billing and receiving reimbursement.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] For every patient encounter, providers must record both ICD codes to identify the diagnosis and CPT codes to document the treatment.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Given the vast number of codes—approximately 70,000 for ICD and over 10,000 for CPT—using advanced medical billing software is recommended to streamline the coding process, reduce errors, and ensure compliance with current standards.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] These steps set the stage for efficient claims submission and payment, forming the backbone of the billing cycle.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Once a patient's visit is complete and they check out, the next step is to compile all the relevant information into a document called a superbill.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] This document serves as the foundation for the reimbursement claim submitted to the payor.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The superbill includes essential details about the provider, the patient, and the visit, ensuring that the claim is complete and accurate for efficient processing.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] By consolidating this information into the superbill, healthcare providers create a structured summary that facilitates claim submission and ensures proper documentation for payor review.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] This step is vital in maintaining accuracy and minimizing errors during the medical billing process.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Using the superbill, the medical biller creates a detailed claim and submits it to the insurance company for reimbursement.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Accuracy and completeness are critical during this step to ensure the claim is accepted on the first submission—referred to as a clean claim.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Achieving a high clean claims rate is a key metric for measuring the efficiency of the billing cycle.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Creation of the claim is where medical billing most directly overlaps with medical coding because billers take the ICD or CPT codes used by medical coders and create the claim.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Once the payor receives the claim, they review it to determine whether it is accepted, denied, or rejected.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Accepted claims are processed for payment.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Payment amounts depend on the specifics of the patient's insurance plan and may not cover the entire billed amount.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] These claims are properly filed but do not meet the payor's criteria for payment.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Common reasons include billing for services not covered by the plan, highlighting the importance of verifying insurance coverage during patient registration.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Denied claims require investigation to identify the issue and prevent future occurrences.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Rejected claims cannot be processed, typically due to errors or omissions in the filing process.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Unlike denied claims, rejected claims must be corrected and resubmitted.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Failure to address rejected claims can lead to significant revenue loss, making timely rework essential.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] After the payor processes the claim and pays their portion, any remaining balance is billed to the patient in a separate statement.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Ideally, patients will promptly settle their accounts, completing the billing cycle.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] However, delays or non-payments are common, requiring providers to follow up to ensure full reimbursement.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] In order to capture revenue that might otherwise be lost, practices follow up on outstanding claims and patient statements and reduce payment barriers to make the process as simple as possible for patients.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Implementing a patient portal with online payment options can streamline the process, allowing patients to pay their bills at their convenience.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] A self-service system encourages on-time payments and reduces the likelihood of accounts being sent to collections.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Consistent follow-ups and clear communication help address common billing issues and improve overall payment rates.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Having an efficient follow-up system helps minimize revenue leakage and keeps the billing cycle running smoothly.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] A practice that has interactions with the patient must now, under HIPAA law 1996, send most billing claims for services via electronic means.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Prior to actually performing service and billing a patient, the care provider may use software to check the eligibility of the patient for the intended services with the patient's insurance company.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] This process uses the same standards and technologies as an electronic claims transmission with small changes to the transmission format.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] This format is known specifically as an X12-270 Health Care Eligibility & Benefit Inquiry transaction.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] A response to an eligibility request is returned by the payor through a direct electronic connection, or more commonly their website.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] This is called an X12-271 Health Care Eligibility & Benefit Response transaction.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Most practice management/EM software will automate this transmission, hiding the process from the user.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] This first transaction for a claim for services is known technically as X12-837 or ANSI-837.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] This contains a large amount of data regarding the provider interaction, as well as reference information about the practice and the patient.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Following that submission, the payor will respond with an X12-997, simply acknowledging that the claim's submission was received and that it was accepted for further processing.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] When the claim(s) are actually adjudicated by the payor, the payor will ultimately respond with a X12-835 transaction, which shows the line-items of the claim that will be paid or denied; if paid, the amount; and if denied, the reason.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] In order to be clear on the payment of a medical billing claim, the health care provider or medical biller must have complete knowledge of different insurance plans that insurance companies are offering, and the laws and regulations that preside over them.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Large insurance companies can have up to 15 different plans contracted with one provider.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] When providers agree to accept an insurance company's plan, the contractual agreement includes many details, including fee schedules which dictate what the insurance company will pay the provider for covered procedures, and other rules such as timely filing guidelines.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Providers typically charge more for services than what has been negotiated by the physician and the insurance company, so the expected payment from the insurance company for services is reduced.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The amount that is paid by the insurance is known as an allowed amount.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] For example, although a psychiatrist may charge $80.00 for a medication management session, the insurance may only allow $50.00, and so a $30.00 reduction (known as a provider write-off or contractual adjustment) would be assessed.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] After payment has been made, a provider will typically receive an Explanation of Benefits (EOB) or Electronic Remittance Advice (ERA) along with the payment from the insurance company that outlines these transactions.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The insurance payment is further reduced if the patient has a copay, deductible, or a coinsurance.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] If the patient in the previous example had a $5.00 copay, the physician would be paid $45.00 by the insurance company.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The physician is then responsible for collecting the out-of-pocket expense from the patient.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] If the patient had a $500.00 deductible, the contracted amount of $50.00 would not be paid by the insurance company.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Instead, this amount would be the patient's responsibility to pay, and subsequent charges would also be the patient's responsibility, until his or her expenses totaled $500.00.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] At that point, the deductible is met, and the insurance would issue payment for future services.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] A coinsurance is a percentage of the allowed amount that the patient must pay.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] It is most often applied to surgical and/or diagnostic procedures.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Using the above example, a coinsurance of 20% would have the patient owing $10.00 and the insurance company owing $40.00.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Steps have been taken in recent years to make the billing process clearer for patients.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The Healthcare Financial Management Association (HFMA) has a Patient-Friendly Billing project to help healthcare providers create more informative and simpler bills for patients.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Additionally, as the consumer-driven health movement gains momentum, payors and providers are exploring new ways to integrate patients into the billing process in a clearer, more straightforward manner.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Some providers outsource their medical billing to third parties, known as medical billing companies, which provide medical billing services.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] One goal of these entities is to reduce the amount of paperwork for medical staff and to increase efficiency, providing the practice with the ability to grow.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] The billing services which can be outsourced include regular invoicing, insurance verification, collections assistance, referral coordination, and reimbursement tracking.
[src:icd-coding/medical-billing] Practices have achieved cost savings through group purchasing organizations (GPO).
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] A **medical classification** is used to transform descriptions of medical diagnoses or procedures into standardized statistical code in a process known as clinical coding.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Diagnosis classifications list diagnosis codes, which are used to track diseases and other health conditions, inclusive of chronic diseases such as diabetes mellitus and heart disease, and infectious diseases such as norovirus, the flu, and athlete's foot.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Procedure classifications list procedure codes, which are used to capture interventional data.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] There are country specific standards and international classification systems.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Many different medical classifications exist, though they occur in two main groupings: *Statistical classifications* and *Nomenclatures*.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] A statistical classification brings together similar clinical concepts and groups them into categories.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The number of categories is limited so that the classification does not become too big.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] An example of this is used by the International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health Problems (known as ICD).
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] ICD-10 groups diseases of the circulatory system into one "chapter", known as Chapter IX, covering codes I00–I99.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] One of the codes in this chapter (I47.1) has the code title (rubric) *Supraventricular tachycardia*.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] However, there are several other clinical concepts that are also classified here.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Among them are paroxysmal atrial tachycardia, paroxysmal junctional tachycardia, auricular tachycardia and nodal tachycardia.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Another feature of statistical classifications is the provision of residual categories for "other" and "unspecified" conditions that do not have a specific category in the particular classification.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] In a nomenclature there is a separate listing and code for every clinical concept.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] So, in the previous example, each of the listed tachycardias would have its own code.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] This makes nomenclatures unwieldy for compiling health statistics.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The World Health Organization (WHO) maintains several internationally endorsed classifications designed to facilitate the comparison of health related data within and across populations and over time as well as the compilation of nationally consistent data.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Some of these international standards have been revised and adapted by various countries for national use.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Derived classifications are based on the WHO reference classifications (i.e., ICD and ICF).
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Several countries have developed their own version of WHO-FIC publications, which go beyond a local language translation.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Related classifications in the WHO-FIC are those that partially refer to the reference classifications, e.g., only at specific levels.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] ICD versions before ICD-9 are not in use anywhere.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] ICD-9 was published in 1977, and superseded by ICD-10 in 1994.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The last version of ICD-10 was published in 2019, and it was replaced by ICD-11 on 1 January 2022.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] As of February 2022, 35 of the 194 member states have made the transition to the latest version of the ICD.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The International Classification of Procedures in Medicine (ICPM) is a procedural classification that has not updated since 1989, and will be replaced by ICHI.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] National adaptions of the ICPM includes OPS-301, which is the official German procedural classification.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] International Classification of External Causes of Injury (ICECI) was last updated in 2003 and, with the development ICD-11, is no longer maintained.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The concepts of ICECI are represented within ICD-11 as extension codes.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The categories in a diagnosis classification classify diseases, disorders, symptoms and medical signs.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The categories in a procedure classification classify specific health interventions undertaken by health professionals.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Drugs are often grouped into drug classes.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] National Drug File-Reference Terminology was a terminology maintained by the Veterans Health Administration (VHA).
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Medication Reference Terminology (MED-RT) is a terminology created and maintained by Veterans Health Administration in the United States.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] In 2018, it replaced NDF-RT that was used during 2005–2017.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Med-RT is not included in RxNorm but is included in National Library of Medicine's UMLS Metathesaurus.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Prior 2017, NDF-RT was included in RxNorm.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The first release of MED-RT was in the spring of 2018.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The Systematized Nomenclature of Medicine (SNOMED) is the most widely recognised nomenclature in healthcare.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Its current version, SNOMED Clinical Terms (SNOMED CT), is intended to provide a set of concepts and relationships that offers a common reference point for comparison and aggregation of data about the health care process.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] SNOMED CT is often described as a reference terminology.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] SNOMED CT contains more than 311,000 active concepts with unique meanings and formal logic-based definitions organised into hierarchies.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] SNOMED CT can be used by anyone with an Affiliate License, 40 low income countries defined by the World Bank or qualifying research, humanitarian and charitable projects.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] SNOMED CT is designed to be managed by computer, and it is a complex relationship concepts.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The International Classification of Disease (ICD) is the most widely recognized medical classification.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Maintained by the World Health Organization (WHO), its primary purpose is to categorise diseases for morbidity and mortality reporting.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] However the coded data is often used for other purposes too; including reimbursement practices such as medical billing.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] ICD has a hierarchical structure, and coding in this context, is the term applied when representations are assigned to the words they represent.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Coding diagnoses and procedures is the assignment of codes from a code set that follows the rules of the underlying classification or other coding guidelines.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The current version of the ICD, ICD-10, was endorsed by WHO in 1990.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] WHO Member states began using the ICD-10 classification system from 1994 for both morbidity and mortality reporting.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The exception was the US, who only began using it for reporting mortality in 1999 whilst continuing to use ICD-9-CM for morbidity reporting.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The US only adopted its version of ICD-10 in October 2015.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The delay meant it was unable to compare US morbidity data with the rest of the world during this period.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The next major version of the ICD, ICD-11, was ratified by the 72nd World Health Assembly on 25 May 2019, and member countries have been able to report data using ICD-11 codes since 1 January 2022.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] ICD-11 is a fully digital product with integration of clinical terminology and classification.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] It allows documentation at any level of detail.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] It includes extension codes, a terminology system, with medicaments, chemicals, infections agents, histopathology, anatomy and mechanisms, objects and animals, and other elements that serve to describe sources of injury or harm.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] SNOMED CT and ICD were originally designed for different purposes and each should be used for the purposes for which they were designed.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] As a core terminology for the EHR, SNOMED CT and ICD-11 provide a common language that enables a consistent way of capturing, and sharing health data across specialities and sites of care.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] SNOMED is a highly detailed terminology designed for input not reporting, without a specific use case.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] ICD-11 and SNOMED, are clinically based, and document whatever is needed for patient care.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] In contrast to SNOMED, ICD-11 allows full clinical documentation while permitting internationally agreed statistical aggregation for specific use cases.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] SNOMED CT and ICD are used directly by healthcare providers during the process of care, in addition, ICD can be also used for coding after the episode of care, in lower technology environments.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] SNOMED CT has multiple hierarchy, whereas there is single primary hierarchy for ICD-11 with alternative multiple hierarchies.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] SNOMED CT concepts are defined logically by their attributes, as is the case in ICD-11, that in addition has textual rules and definitions.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] The National Library of Medicine (NLM) maps ICD-9-CM, ICD-10-CM, ICD-10-PCS, and other classification systems to SNOMED.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Data Mapping is the process of identifying relationships between two distinct data models.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Veterinary medical codes include the VeNom Coding Group, the U.S.
[src:icd-coding/medical-classification] Animal Hospital Codes, and the Veterinary Extension to SNOMED CT (VetSCT).
